The `erase` function returns an iterator pointing to the element following the one removed. This is assigned to `it`.After erasing, `it` will be valid only if there are more elements after the erased element. If the erased element was the last one, `it` will equal `requestMsg.end()`. And again a `it++` could lead to a crash/ undefined behaviour.

instead i guess you could do an increment of the iterator only when you don't erase
..may be something like this ?

```
for (auto it = requestMsg.begin(); it != requestMsg.end();)
{
    auto msg = *it;
    if (msg->key == key)
    {
        it = endpointMessageQueues[eid]->requestQueue.erase(it); // erase and get the next valid iterator
        instanceIdDb.free(key.eid, key.instanceId);
        return PLDM_SUCCESS;
    }
    else
    {
        ++it; // increment iterator only if not erasing
    }
}
```
